{"title_page": "The Brain Leeches", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Brain Leeches\n| image          = \n| alt            = \n| director       = [[Fred Olen Ray]]\n| producer       = Fred Olen Ray\n| writer         = Jim Kennedy<br>[[Brad Linaweaver]]<br>Fred Olen Ray\n| based on       = \n| starring       = Paul Jones<br>Marcia Scott<br>Ray Starr\n| music          = Paul Jones<br>Sugar Lee<br>[[Modest Mussorgsky]]\n| cinematography = Marvin Levine<br>John Raber<br>Fred Olen Ray<br><small>(as Fred Ray)</small>\n| editing        = \n| studio         = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = \n| runtime        = 55 minutes\n| country        = \n| language       = English\n| budget         = $298.00\n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''The Brain Leeches''''' is an [[low-budget film|low-budget]]  [[science fiction film|science fiction]] [[exploitation film]] directed by [[Fred Olen Ray]] and starring Paul Jones, Marcia Scott & Ray Starr. It has a running time of 55 minutes, and was completed on a budget of $298.00. The film was shown publicly only once, although it has since become available through distributors. The project proved to be a turning point in the careers of two of the principals.\n\n==Plot==\nA former nuclear scientist turned pro-wrestler does battle with invading aliens who are taking over the brains of folks in a small town.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" />\n\n==Production==\n===Watershed moment===\nThe project proved to be a [[Tipping point (sociology)|watershed moment]] for two of the principals. Political essayist [[Brad Linaweaver]] received his first original story credit (for film) for ''The Brain Leeches''. The experience changed the trajectory of Linaweaver's career path, emphasizing film and science fiction writing for the rest of his life.<ref name=\"Investigator\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodinvestigator.com/2007/linaweaver.htm|title=Libertarian Screenwriter Brad Linaweaver Slams Neocons|publisher=Hollywood Investigator|date=August 12, 2007|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Memorium\">{{citeweb|url= https://amazingstories.com/2019/09/in-memoriam-brad-linaweaver/|title=In Memoriam-Brad Linaweaver|publisher=AmazingStories.com|date=September 12, 2019|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Locus\">{{cite web|url=https://locusmag.com/2019/09/brad-linaweaver-1952-2019/|title=Brad Linaweaver (1952-2019)|publisher=Locus Publications|date=September 3, 2019|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>  The film also jump started the career of prodigious Hollywood director/producer (and sometimes professional wrestler<ref name=\"Boggs2014\">{{cite book|author=Johnny D. Boggs|title=Jesse James and the Movies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-TLXYhM3cTkC&pg=PA225|date=10 January 2014|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-8496-6|page=225}}</ref>) Fred Olen Ray, who is also known for having loaned [[Quentin Tarantino]] his first 16mm camera to make ''[[My Best Friend's Birthday]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2007/film/news/q-a-with-tarantino-when-he-was-mr-green-1117961178/|title=Q&A with Tarantino\u2026when he was Mr. Green|first=Steve|last=Gaydos|website=Variety|date=14 March 2007|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The association and collaboration between Linaweaver and Ray continued until Linaweaver's death in 2019.<ref name=\"Locus\" />\n\n===Low-budget===\nPrincipal photography took place in 1978.<ref name=\"OS\" /> The film was shot using an old [[Auricon|Auricon 16mm camera]], and (expired) nine-year-old [[black and white]] film stock obtained from Ray's employer, an [[Orlando, Florida]] television station.<ref name=\"Ray1991\">{{cite book|author=Fred Olen Ray|title=The New Poverty Row: Independent Filmmakers as Distributors|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H9GknfDYd4sC&pg=PA176|date=1 January 1991|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-89950-628-9|page=176}}</ref><ref name=\"Quarles2010\">{{cite book|author=Mike Quarles|title=Down and Dirty: Hollywood's Exploitation Filmmakers and Their Movies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L5iRMlzjbSEC&pg=PA80|date=21 June 2010|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-6257-5|page=80}}</ref> The alien invaders were represented by large rubber ants, purchased at a [[dime store]] for 19 cents each.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /><ref name=\"Ants\">{{cite newspaper|url=https://orlandosentinel.newspapers.com/clip/16774509/the-brain-leeches/|title=An eye for an eye|publisher=[[The Orlando Sentinel]]|date=June 11, 1978|page=388|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Earthlings under mind control by the aliens were portrayed as having all-white eyes. The [[special effect]] was achieved by applying white tape to the actors' eyelids.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /> The destruction of the alien headquarters (the TV station where Ray worked) was depicted using stock footage of a nuclear explosion, from an old 16mm documentary found in the television station film archive.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /> The film score is a [[public domain]] recording of [[Moussorgsky]]'s [[Pictures at an Exhibition]], taken directly from a \"cheap record album\". According to Ray: \"No effort was made to synchronize any of the music to the picture\".<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /> Portions of the film were shot at a bar (The Foxhead Tavern) in Orlando.<ref name=\"OS\">{{cite newspaper|url=https://orlandosentinel.newspapers.com/clip/16774450/the-brain-leeches/|title=\"The Brain Leeches\"|publisher=[[The Orlando Sentinel]]|page=133|date=May 28, 1978|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> \n\nProduction of ''The Brain Leeches'' was completed, on budget, for $298.00.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /><ref name=\"Quarles2010\"/>\n\n==Distribution==\nIn 1991, Ray stated that ''The Brain Leeches'' had been shown publicly only one time, and that it would never be released for distribution.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /> However, more than 30 years after its first showing, copies of the film have become available through distributors such as Sinister Cinema.com.<ref name=\"Locus\"/><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.sinistercinema.com/product.asp?specific=33963|title=Sci Fi Brain Leeches, The*|publisher=Sinister Cinema.com|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*Paul Jones as Dr. John Hayes\n*Marcia Scott as Susan\n*Ray Starr as Rusty Fender\n*Jennifer Knight as Rose\n*[[Brad Linaweaver]] as Billy Johnson\n*[[Fred Olen Ray]] (as Brian Wolfe) as Tom<ref name=\"Ants\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*''[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0075780/?ref_=fn_al_tt_1 The Brain Leeches]'' at [[Internet Movie Database]]\n*''[http://movies.msn.com/movies/movie/the-brain-leeches/ The Brain Leeches]'' at Movies.msn.com\n\n{{Fred Olen Ray}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brain Leeches}}\n[[Category:1970s science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Fred Olen Ray]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction horror films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Brain Leeches\n| image          = \n| alt            = \n| director       = [[Fred Olen Ray]]\n| producer       = Fred Olen Ray\n| writer         = Jim Kennedy<br>[[Brad Linaweaver]]<br>Fred Olen Ray\n| based on       = \n| starring       = Paul Jones<br>Marcia Scott<br>Ray Starr\n| music          = Paul Jones<br>Sugar Lee<br>[[Modest Mussorgsky]]\n| cinematography = Marvin Levine<br>John Raber<br>Fred Olen Ray<br><small>(as Fred Ray)</small>\n| editing        = \n| studio         = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = \n| runtime        = 55 minutes\n| country        = \n| language       = English\n| budget         = $298.00\n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''The Brain Leeches''''' is an [[low-budget film|low-budget]]  [[science fiction film|science fiction]] [[exploitation film]] directed by [[Fred Olen Ray]] and starring Paul Jones, Marcia Scott & Ray Starr. It has a running time of 55 minutes, and was completed on a budget of $298.00. The film was shown publicly only once, although it has since become available through distributors. The project proved to be a turning point in the careers of two of the principals.\n\n==Plot==\nA former nuclear scientist turned pro-wrestler does battle with invading aliens who are taking over the brains of folks in a small town.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" />\n\n==Production==\n===Watershed moment===\nThe project proved to be a [[Tipping point (sociology)|watershed moment]] for two of the principals. Political essayist [[Brad Linaweaver]] received his first original story credit (for film) for ''The Brain Leeches''. The experience changed the trajectory of Linaweaver's career path, emphasizing film and science fiction writing for the rest of his life.<ref name=\"Investigator\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodinvestigator.com/2007/linaweaver.htm|title=Libertarian Screenwriter Brad Linaweaver Slams Neocons|publisher=Hollywood Investigator|date=August 12, 2007|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Memorium\">{{citeweb|url= https://amazingstories.com/2019/09/in-memoriam-brad-linaweaver/|title=In Memoriam-Brad Linaweaver|publisher=AmazingStories.com|date=September 12, 2019|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Locus\">{{cite web|url=https://locusmag.com/2019/09/brad-linaweaver-1952-2019/|title=Brad Linaweaver (1952-2019)|publisher=Locus Publications|date=September 3, 2019|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>  The film also jump started the career of prodigious Hollywood director/producer (and sometimes professional wrestler<ref name=\"Boggs2014\">{{cite book|author=Johnny D. Boggs|title=Jesse James and the Movies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-TLXYhM3cTkC&pg=PA225|date=10 January 2014|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-8496-6|page=225}}</ref>) Fred Olen Ray, who is also known for having loaned [[Quentin Tarantino]] his first 16mm camera to make ''[[My Best Friend's Birthday]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2007/film/news/q-a-with-tarantino-when-he-was-mr-green-1117961178/|title=Q&A with Tarantino\u2026when he was Mr. Green|first=Steve|last=Gaydos|website=Variety|date=14 March 2007|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The association and collaboration between Linaweaver and Ray continued until Linaweaver's death in 2019.<ref name=\"Locus\" />\n\n===Low-budget===\nPrincipal photography took place in 1978.<ref name=\"OS\" /> The film was shot using an old [[Auricon|Auricon 16mm camera]], and (expired) nine-year-old [[black and white]] film stock obtained from Ray's employer, an [[Orlando, Florida]] television station.<ref name=\"Ray1991\">{{cite book|author=Fred Olen Ray|title=The New Poverty Row: Independent Filmmakers as Distributors|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H9GknfDYd4sC&pg=PA176|date=1 January 1991|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-89950-628-9|page=176}}</ref><ref name=\"Quarles2010\">{{cite book|author=Mike Quarles|title=Down and Dirty: Hollywood's Exploitation Filmmakers and Their Movies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L5iRMlzjbSEC&pg=PA80|date=21 June 2010|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-6257-5|page=80}}</ref> The alien invaders were represented by large rubber ants, purchased at a [[dime store]] for 19 cents each.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /><ref name=\"Ants\">{{cite newspaper|url=https://orlandosentinel.newspapers.com/clip/16774509/the-brain-leeches/|title=An eye for an eye|publisher=[[The Orlando Sentinel]]|date=June 11, 1978|page=388|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Earthlings under mind control by the aliens were portrayed as having all-white eyes. The [[special effect]] was achieved by applying white tape to the actors' eyelids.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /> The destruction of the alien headquarters (the TV station where Ray worked) was depicted using stock footage of a nuclear explosion, from an old 16mm documentary found in the television station film archive.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /> The film score is a [[public domain]] recording of [[Moussorgsky]]'s [[Pictures at an Exhibition]], taken directly from a \"cheap record album\". According to Ray: \"No effort was made to synchronize any of the music to the picture\".<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /> Portions of the film were shot at a bar (The Foxhead Tavern) in Orlando.<ref name=\"OS\">{{cite newspaper|url=https://orlandosentinel.newspapers.com/clip/16774450/the-brain-leeches/|title=\"The Brain Leeches\"|publisher=[[The Orlando Sentinel]]|page=133|date=May 28, 1978|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> \n\nProduction of ''The Brain Leeches'' was completed, on budget, for $298.00.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /><ref name=\"Quarles2010\"/>\n\n==Distribution==\nIn 1991, Ray stated that ''The Brain Leeches'' had been shown publicly only one time, and that it would never be released for distribution.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /> However, more than 30 years after its first showing, copies of the film have become available through distributors such as Sinister Cinema.com.<ref name=\"Locus\"/><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.sinistercinema.com/product.asp?specific=33963|title=Sci Fi BRAIN LEECHES, THE*|publisher=Sinister Cinema.com|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>  \n\n==Cast==\n*Paul Jones as Dr. John Hayes\n*Marcia Scott as Susan\n*Ray Starr as Rusty Fender\n*Jennifer Knight as Rose\n*[[Brad Linaweaver]] as Billy Johnson\n*[[Fred Olen Ray]] (as Brian Wolfe) as Tom<ref name=\"Ants\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*''[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0075780/?ref_=fn_al_tt_1 The Brain Leeches]'' at [[Internet Movie Database]]\n*''[http://movies.msn.com/movies/movie/the-brain-leeches/ The Brain Leeches]'' at Movies.msn.com\n\n{{Fred Olen Ray}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brain Leeches}}\n[[Category:1970s science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Fred Olen Ray]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction horror films]]\n", "name_user": "Gulbenk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDistribution", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Brain_Leeches"}
{"title_page": "Chennai 600028", "text_new": "{{unreliable sources|date=November 2017}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Chennai 600028<br>A Venkat Prabhu Film\n| image          = Chennai600028.jpg\n| caption        = Promotional poster\n| director       = [[Venkat Prabhu]]\n| writer         = [[Venkat Prabhu]]\n| narrator       = [[S. P. Balasubrahmanyam]]\n| producer       = [[S. P. B. Charan]]<br />J. K. Saravana\n| starring       = [[Jai (actor)|Jai]]<br />[[Shiva (actor)|Shiva]]<br />[[Premji Amaren|Premji]]<br />[[Nithin Sathya]]<br />[[Aravind Akash]]<br />[[Vijay Vasanth]]<br />[[Vijayalakshmi (Tamil actress)|Vijayalakshmi]]<br />[[Ajay Raj]]<br />Prasanna<br />Ranjith<br />Karthik<br />Arun\n| music          = <small>'''Background score:'''</small><br>Premji Amaren<br><small>'''Original songs:'''</small><br>[[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]<br />Premji Amaren (1 Song)<br />\n| editing        = <small>'''Film editor:'''</small><br>[[B. Lenin]]<br/><small>'''Digital & Avid editor:'''</small><br>[[Praveen K. L.]]<br/>[[Srikanth.N.B]]\n| cinematography = [[Sakthi Saravanan]]\n| studio         = [[S. P. B. Charan|Capital Film Works]]\n| distributor    = Tantra films\n| released       = {{film date|2007|04|27|df=y|ref1=}}\n| runtime        = 141 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n| budget         = {{INR}}1.65 crore<ref>{{cite web|title=The new darlings of Kollywood|url=http://www.tehelka.com/story_main50.asp?filename=hub090711The.asp|accessdate=5 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707041158/http://www.tehelka.com/story_main50.asp?filename=hub090711The.asp#|archive-date=7 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| gross          = <!--Must be attributed to a reliable published source with an established reputation for fact-checking. No blogs, no IMDb.-->\n}}\n\n'''''Chennai 600028''''' is a 2007 [[Tamil language|Tamil-language]] [[sports comedy]] film written and directed by [[Venkat Prabhu]], in his directorial debut. The film stars [[Jai (actor)|Jai]], [[Shiva (actor)|Shiva]], [[Premgi Amaren|Premji]], [[Aravind Akash]], [[Nithin Sathya]] and newcomers [[Ajay Raj]], Ranjith, [[Vijay Vasanth]], Prasanna, [[Inigo Prabakaran]], Karthik and Arun in the lead along with [[Vijayalakshmi Ahathian|Vijayalakshmi]], daughter of [[National Film Award (India)|National Film Award]]-winning director [[Agathiyan]], and Kristine Zedek, making their acting debut as well.<ref name=oneindia>{{cite web|url=http://popcorn.oneindia.in/movie-cast/4318/chennai-600028.html|title=Chennai 600028 Cast & Crew|accessdate=3 October 2011|publisher=[[Oneindia.in]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090614050917/http://popcorn.oneindia.in/movie-cast/4318/chennai-600028.html|archivedate=14 June 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film was produced by [[S. P. B. Charan]] along with J. K. Saravana, a Singapore-based award-winning producer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/35687.html|title=A creative force from Singapore|publisher=indiaglitz.com|accessdate=2009-07-28}}</ref> The film's score and soundtrack were composed by [[Premji Amaran]] and [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]], respectively.\n\nThe film is based on [[street cricket]] played in India, focussing on various themes as friendship, love and [[sports rivalry|rivalry]] in a suburban area.<ref name=\"behindwoods.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-slide-shows/movie-1/top-collection/chennai-28.html |title=CHENNAI 28 BOX OFFICE TOP 10 OF 2007 - Behindwoods.com|publisher=Behindwoods.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> Following its theatrical release on 27 April 2007, it received critical acclaim and emerged a surprise [[sleeper hit]], running successfully for more than one year in theaters,<ref name=\"behindwoods.com\"/><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cinesouth.com/specials/specials/tamilcinima2007tam.shtml |title=Tamil cinema in 2007 \u2013 half year report |publisher=Cinesouth.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> whilst going on to achieve [[cult film|cult status]] in the subsequent years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-slide-shows/movie-4/formulaic-films/chennai-28.html |title=Movies that beat the odds - Behindwoods.com|publisher=Behindwoods.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> The film's title is derived from the [[Postal Index Number|pincode]] for [[Mandaveli]], a suburb of [[Chennai]], where the story takes place. The success of the film gained the relatively unknown actors &mdash; Jai, Shiva, Premji and Nithin Sathya, newcomers Vijayalakshmi, Vijay Vasanth and the director Venkat Prabhu popularity.\n\nUpon release, the film was dubbed into [[Telugu language|Telugu]] and released as ''Kodithe Kottalira''.<ref name=\"Telugu Cinema in 2007\">{{cite news | title=hindu.com| work=Friday Review - Cricket theme goes on| url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2007/07/13/stories/2007071350160400.htm | location=Chennai, India| date=13 July 2007}}</ref> The film was also remade in Bengali as ''[[Le Chakka]]'' (2010),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/1100912/jsp/calcutta/story_12922038.jsp|title=Copycat chronicles|date=12 September 2010|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=17 June 2018|location=Calcutta}}</ref> [[cinema of Sri Lanka|Sinhalese]] as ''[[Super Six (film)|Super Six]]'' (2012),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/cricket/ravichandran-ashwin-and-murali-vijay-to-make-special-appearances-in-a-tamil-film|title=Ravichandran Ashwin and Murali Vijay to make special appearances in a Tamil film|date=2016-04-05|access-date=2018-06-17}}</ref> and in Kannada as ''[[Bangalore 560023]]'' (2015).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Chennai-600028-to-be-remade-in-Kannada/articleshow/36190919.cms|title=Chennai 600028 to be remade in Kannada - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-06-17}}</ref> A sequel for the film, ''[[Chennai 600028 II: Second Innings]]'', has also since been released.\n\n==Plot==\nThe story revolves around two local cricket league teams that compete against each other in local matches and consider each other as sworn enemies. Royapuram Rockers are on top of the chain and keep bashing the Sharks year after year. The heroes of the movie are the Sharks' team.\n\nThe story begins when Raghu's ([[Jai (actor)|Jai]]) parents move from Royapuram to Visalakshi Thottam, Chennai 600 028. Raghu is a member of the Royapuram Rockers Cricket team, and a college student living with his parents. He has no choice but to move with them although he detests the area. He is not very excited at the prospect of living in the same area as his sworn enemies. Raghu is faithful to his teammates, but they ignore him because of the distance. Angered at being replaced by a new guy in the team in one of the matches, Raghu estranges himself from cricket and the Rockers.\n\nRaghu informs of Pazhani's ([[Nithin Sathya]]) sister Selvi's ([[Vijayalakshmi (Tamil actress)|Vijayalakshmi]]) love for Karthik ([[Shiva (actor)|Shiva]]) to him. This incident initiates Raghu's friendship with a few Sharks team players and eventually gets induced into the team. Raghu practices with the Sharks to play against the Rockers in the upcoming Radio Mirchi trophy. Pazhani, who soon comes to know of his sister's and Karthik's love affair is disappointed and then there is a tiff amongst the friends. The team splits up for a while, but Karthik apologizes to Pazhani and they make up. The team is united again and they start practicing for the trophy once again. Unfortunately, Karthik gets stabbed by his brother's enemies and is rendered unfit to play the match. Pazhani replaces Karthik as the captain and the team heads for the match.\n\nUnder tight pressure and with a nail biting finish, the Sharks finally defeat the Rockers in the semi-finals of the tournament. In the finals they meet their enemies , a bunch of school kids named Bad Boys-II who practice by bunking school to play cricket on the beach. The kids are really good and the Sharks know it because they have lost to them once before and that too very badly...\n\nThe movie ends with the team really struggling to keep it up in the game.\n\n==Cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Jai (actor)|Jai]] as Raghuvaran \"Raghu\"\n* [[Shiva (actor)|Shiva]] as Karthik\n* [[Premji Amaran|Premji]] as Seenivasan \"Seenu\"\n* [[Aravind Akash]] as Aravind\n* [[Nithin Sathya]] as Pazhani\n* [[Vijay Vasanth]] as Gopi\n* Ezhumalai as Ajay Raj\n* Prasanna as Shanmugham\n* Ranjith as Imran\n* Arun as Uday\n* Karthik as Arivazhagan \"Arivu\"\n* [[Sampath Raj]] as Guna\n* [[Ilavarasu]] as Manohar\n* [[Vijayalakshmi Ahathian|Vijayalakshmi]] as Selvi\n* Kristine Zedek as Swetha\n* [[Badava Gopi]] as Commentator\n* [[Sakthi Saravanan]] as Aravind's boss\n* [[Inigo Prabakaran]] as John (Rockers's captain)\n* [[Mai Prakash]] as Rocker's team player\n* Sundar as Jeeva\n* [[Viraj (actor)|Hari Prashanth]] as Hari, Bad Boys' captain\n* [[S. N. Surendar]] as Sampath, Raghu's father\n* Srilatha as Durga, Raghu's mother\n* [[Shanmugasundaram]] as Sports minister\n* [[Mirchi Senthil]] as Radio Mirchi RJ (special appearance)\n* [[Kalyan (choreographer)|Kalyan]] special appearance in \"Saroja Saman Nikalo\" song\n{{colend}}\n\n==Production==\n''Chennai 600028'' is the directorial debut of Venkat Prabhu.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/features/Interviews/interview-5/director/venkat-prahbu.html|title=Don\u2019t expect another Chennai 28 from Saroja|website=Behindwoods|access-date=2018-06-17}}</ref> He initially titled the film as ''Enga Area Ulla Varaadha'' (''Don't come into our territory''), but lyricist [[Vaali (poet)|Vaali]] was critical of the idea, feeling that the title was \"negative\" sounding. Subsequently, the film was renamed as ''Chennai 600028'', with the idea of including the area's postcode taken from the title of the American television series ''[[Beverly Hills, 90210]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-columns/The-kadalai-man/article14028724.ece|title=The kadalai man|first=Bhargavii|last=Mani|date=30 January 2016|publisher=|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref> Venkat Prabhu felt the new title was \"more apt and universal\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2007/jul/11sld2.htm|title=rediff.com: 'Rajni Sir enjoyed Chennai 600028'|website=www.rediff.com}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Chennai 600028\n| type         = soundtrack\n| artist       = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = <div style=\"white-space: nowrap;\">19 February 2007 {{small|([[India]])}}<br />23 February 2007 {{small|(Singapore and [[Malaysia]])}}\n| recorded     = 2006\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length       = 37:20\n| language     = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| label        = Five Star Audio\n| producer     = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n| prev_title   = [[Deepavali (2007 film)|Deepavali]]\n| prev_year    = 2007\n| next_title   = [[Aadavari Matalaku Ardhalu Verule]]\n| next_year    = 2007\n}}\n\nThe film's score was composed by Venkat Prabhu's brother, [[Premji Amaran]], while his cousin, [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]] composed the soundtrack, which also featured two tracks that were rearranged by Premji. The soundtrack album, featuring 9 tracks, released on 19 February 2007 in [[India]] and four days later in Singapore and [[Malaysia]], on 23 February 2007.<ref name=\"Indiaglitzaudio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/29324.html|title=Chennai-600028 audio on Feb 19|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=indiaglitz.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2009-07-28}}</ref> The audio was launched at the radio station [[Radio Mirchi]], broadcasting all the songs live, which was said to be the first time in India.<ref name=\"Indiaglitzaudio\"/> The lyrics were written by [[Vaali (poet)|'Kavignar' Vaali]] and [[Gangai Amaran]], father of Venkat Prabhu. Also, composer [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]] penned the lyrics for the song \"Natpukullae\", besides singing it. 19 singers had rendered their voice for the songs, including Yogi B, DJ Funky Sathiya and SilveStar, two Singaporean rappers, actor [[Karunas]], director Venkat Prabhu and producer S. P. B. Charan.<ref name=oneindia/>\n\nThe album was both critically acclaimed and gained immense popularity upon its release, being described as, \"excellent\", a \"rocking album\"<ref name=\"Indiaglitzreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/musicreview/8805.html|title=Chennai 600028 - A youthful musical journey|publisher=indiaglitz.com|accessdate=2009-07-28}}</ref> and one of the \"aesthetic highlights\" of the film.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2007/05/04/stories/2007050400100200.htm|title=Leading a winning team - Chennai 600028|publisher=indiaglitz.com|accessdate=2009-07-28|location=Chennai, India|date=4 May 2007}}</ref> The songs were said to be a big hit as reportedly 25000 CDs were sold on the very first day,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/29505.html|title=Chennai-600028 audio a big hit|publisher=indiaglitz.com|accessdate=2009-07-28}}</ref> \"ruling the charts\" worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/30209.html|title=Chennai 600028\u2019s Audio Rules Top 10 List Worldwide!|publisher=indiaglitz.com|accessdate=2009-07-28}}</ref> The songs \"Jalsa\" and \"Saroja Saman Nikalo\" were \"rocking the dance floors\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/30417.html|title=\u2018Jalsa Pannungada\u2019 rocks dance floors!|publisher=indiaglitz.com|accessdate=2009-07-28}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| title8 = Jalsa\n| extra9 = [[Shankar Mahadevan]], [[Premji Amaran]]\n| extra8 = [[Sabesh-Murali|Sabesh]], Gana Ulaganathan, Gana Pazhani, [[Karunas]], [[Premji Amaren]]\n| extra7 = [[S. P. B. Charan]], [[Venkat Prabhu]]\n| extra6 = [[Anushka Manchanda]]\n| extra5 = [[Ranjith (singer)|Ranjith]], [[Tippu (singer)|Tippu]], [[Premji Amaran]], [[Haricharan]], [[Karthik (singer)|Karthik]]\n| extra4 = [[S. P. Balasubramanyam]], [[K. S. Chithra]]\n| extra2 = [[Vijay Yesudas]]\n| extra3 = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n| extra1 = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]], Yogi B, DJ Funky Sathiya, SILVEstar\n| lyrics9 = Gangai Amaran\n| lyrics8 = Gangai Amaran\n| lyrics7 = Vaali\n| lyrics6 = Vaali\n| lyrics5 = [[Gangai Amaran]]\n| lyrics4 = Vaali\n| lyrics3 = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n| lyrics2 = Vaali\n| lyrics1 = [[Vaali (poet)|Vaali]]\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| total_length = 37:20\n| length10 = \n| title10 = \n| length9 = 4:15\n| title9 = Saroja Saman Nikalo\n| length8 = 4:08\n| length7 = 5:01\n| title1 = Ulle Vaa\n| title7 = Yaaro\n| length6 = 4:06\n| title6 = Oh! Oh! Ennanamo\n| length5 = 3:57\n| title5 = Jalsa\n| length4 = 5:15\n| title4 = Yaaro\n| length3 = 2:36\n| title3 = Natpukkullae\n| length2 = 4:09\n| title2 = Un Parvai\n| length1 = 3:51\n| note8 = Remix\n| note4 = Love Theme\n| music9 = Yuvan Shankar Raja\n| music8 = Yuvan Shankar Raja {{small|(Remixed by [[Premgi Amaran]])}}\n| music7 = [[Premgi Amaran]]\n| music2 = Yuvan Shankar Raja\n| note7 = Friendship Theme\n| music6 = Yuvan Shankar Raja\n| music5 = Yuvan Shankar Raja\n| music4 = Yuvan Shankar Raja\n| music3 = Yuvan Shankar Raja\n| music1 = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n}}\n\n== Release and reception ==\nChennai 600028 was released on 27 April 2007, and emerged as a major commercial success. Sify in their review stated that \"All the guys who acted in the film are candid and have let their hair down. RJ Shiva is the surprise packet in the film. Venkat Prabhu deserves a pat on his back for making a breezy fun movie which highlights the fact that cricket in India which is a religion for many is also won through team spirit and sacrifice. So go ahead, make your matinee and enjoy the match.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sify.com/movies/chennai-600028-review--pclwoBaajccbf.html|title=Review : (2007)|website=www.sify.com|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref> Filmibeat reviewed it as \"Apart from cricket there is enough space for love, friendship, sentiments and decent comedy in the script.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.filmibeat.com/tamil/movies/chennai-600028/review.html|title=Read Chennai 600028 Movie Reviews and Critics Reviews|website=FilmiBeat|language=en|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref> Baradwaj Rangan reviewed the film as \"A street-cricket saga from a bunch of no-names comes out of nowhere and knocks your socks off.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://baradwajrangan.wordpress.com/2007/05/31/review-chennai-600028/|title=Review: Chennai 600028|date=2007-05-31|website=Baradwaj Rangan|language=en|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref> Writing for Rediff, the review stated as \"The movie is a result of a perfect team effort in every sense. A perfect entertainer, not to be missed.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/2007/apr/30chennai.htm|title=Chennai 600028: An entertainer|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref>\n\nThe film emerged as a [[sleeper hit]] at the box office, and also emerging as the [[cult film|cult status]], in coming years.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"behindwoods.com\" /> The film's 100th day celebrations, took place on 5 August 2007 at [[Chennai Trade Centre]], with [[Rajinikanth]] and [[Kamal Haasan|Kamal Hassan]] being the chief guest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sify.com/movies/chennai-600028-100days-imagegallery-events-jdwmNMfgfcesi.html|title=Chennai 600028-100days|website=Sify|language=en|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref>\n\n== Dubbed versions and remakes ==\n''Chennai 600028'' was dubbed into [[Telugu language|Telugu]] as ''Kodithe Kottalira'' upon release, and the film was remade in [[Bengali language|Bengali]] as ''[[Le Chakka]]'' (2009), and in [[Kannada]] as ''[[Bangalore 560023]]'' (2015). The film was also remade in [[Sinhala language|Sinhalese]] as ''[[Super Six (film)|Super Six]]'' in 2012.\n\n==Sequel==\n{{main|Chennai 600028 II}}\n\nPlans to make a sequel to ''Chennai 600028'' were reported several times in the media, shortly after the first film's release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiaglitz.com/tamil|title=A sequel to Chennai 600028|last=|first=|date=|website=IndiaGlitz.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> It features several cast members from the earlier film including [[Jai (actor)|Jai]], [[Shiva (actor)|Shiva]], [[Premji Amaran|Premji]], [[Aravind Akash]] and [[Nithin Sathya]]. Actors [[Vaibhav Reddy|Vaibhav]], [[Subbu Panchu]], [[Abhinay Vaddi]] were chosen to play supporting roles in the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/kollywood/200416/abhinay-plays-baddie-in-chennai-28-sequel.html|title=Abhinay plays baddie in Chennai-28 sequel!|last=Subhakeerthana|first=S.|date=2016-04-20|website=Deccan Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> Production of the film was officially unveiled on 28 February 2016 and the film was released on 9 December 2016.\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n; [[Vijay Awards]]\n* [[Vijay Award for Best Crew]]\n* [[Vijay Award for Best Find of the Year]] - [[Venkat Prabhu]]\n* Nominated - [[Vijay Award for Best Film]]\n* Nominated - [[Vijay Award for Best Director]] - Venkat Prabhu\n* Nominated - [[Vijay Award for Best Story, Screenplay Writer]] - Venkat Prabhu\n* Nominated - [[Vijay Award for Best Debut Actor]] - [[Shiva (actor)|Shiva]]\n* Nominated - [[Vijay Award for Best Debut Actress]] - [[Vijayalakshmi Ahathian]]\n* Nominated - [[Vijay Award for Best Editor]] - [[B. Lenin]]\n* Nominated - [[Vijay Award for Best Lyricist]] - [[Vaali (poet)|Vaali]]\n* Nominated - [[Vijay Award for Best Male Playback Singer]] - [[S. P. Balasubrahmanyam]]\n* Nominated - [[Vijay Award for Best Choreographer]] - [[Ajay Raj]]\n\n; [[Tamil Nadu State Film Awards]]\n*[[Tamil Nadu State Film Award for Best Family Film]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Enna Kodumai Saravanan Idhu]]\n* [[Kodambakkam, Chennai]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1496380}}\n\n{{Venkat Prabhu}}\n\n[[Category:2007 films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:2000s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:2000s buddy comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s sports comedy films]]\n[[Category:Culture of Chennai]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n[[Category:Films about cricket in India]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Venkat Prabhu]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian buddy films]]\n[[Category:Indian sports comedy films]]\n[[Category:Tamil films remade in other languages]]\n[[Category:2007 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{unreliable sources|date=November 2017}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Chennai 600028<br>A Venkat Prabhu Film\n| image          = Chennai600028.jpg\n| caption        = Promotional poster\n| director       = [[Venkat Prabhu]]\n| writer         = [[Venkat Prabhu]]\n| narrator       = [[S. P. Balasubrahmanyam]]\n| producer       = [[S. P. B. Charan]]<br />J. K. Saravana\n| starring       = [[Jai (actor)|Jai]]<br />[[Shiva (actor)|Shiva]]<br />[[Premji Amaren|Premji]]<br />[[Nithin Sathya]]<br />[[Aravind Akash]]<br />[[Vijay Vasanth]]<br />[[Vijayalakshmi (Tamil actress)|Vijayalakshmi]]<br />[[Ajay Raj]]<br />Prasanna<br />Ranjith<br />Karthik<br />Arun\n| music          = <small>'''Background score:'''</small><br>Premji Amaren<br><small>'''Original songs:'''</small><br>[[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]<br />Premji Amaren (1 Song)<br />\n| editing        = <small>'''Film editor:'''</small><br>[[B. Lenin]]<br/><small>'''Digital & Avid editor:'''</small><br>[[Praveen K. L.]]<br/>[[Srikanth.N.B]]\n| cinematography = [[Sakthi Saravanan]]\n| studio         = [[S. P. B. Charan|Capital Film Works]]\n| distributor    = Tantra films\n| released       = {{film date|2007|04|27|df=y|ref1=}}\n| runtime        = 141 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n| budget         = {{INR}}1.65 crore<ref>{{cite web|title=The new darlings of Kollywood|url=http://www.tehelka.com/story_main50.asp?filename=hub090711The.asp|accessdate=5 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707041158/http://www.tehelka.com/story_main50.asp?filename=hub090711The.asp#|archive-date=7 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| gross          = <!--Must be attributed to a reliable published source with an established reputation for fact-checking. No blogs, no IMDb.-->\n}}\n\n'''''Chennai 600028''''' is a 2007 [[Tamil language|Tamil-language]] [[sports comedy]] film written and directed by [[Venkat Prabhu]], in his directorial debut. The film stars [[Jai (actor)|Jai]], [[Shiva (actor)|Shiva]], [[Premgi Amaren|Premji]], [[Aravind Akash]], [[Nithin Sathya]] and newcomers [[Ajay Raj]], Ranjith, [[Vijay Vasanth]], Prasanna, [[Inigo Prabakaran]], Karthik and Arun in the lead along with [[Vijayalakshmi Ahathian|Vijayalakshmi]], daughter of [[National Film Award (India)|National Film Award]]-winning director [[Agathiyan]], and Kristine Zedek, making their acting debut as well.<ref name=oneindia>{{cite web|url=http://popcorn.oneindia.in/movie-cast/4318/chennai-600028.html|title=Chennai 600028 Cast & Crew|accessdate=3 October 2011|publisher=[[Oneindia.in]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090614050917/http://popcorn.oneindia.in/movie-cast/4318/chennai-600028.html|archivedate=14 June 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film was produced by [[S. P. B. Charan]] along with J. K. Saravana, a Singapore-based award-winning producer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/35687.html|title=A creative force from Singapore|publisher=indiaglitz.com|accessdate=2009-07-28}}</ref> The film's score and soundtrack were composed by [[Premji Amaran]] and [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]], respectively.\n\nThe film is based on [[street cricket]] played in India, focussing on various themes as friendship, love and [[sports rivalry|rivalry]] in a suburban area.<ref name=\"behindwoods.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-slide-shows/movie-1/top-collection/chennai-28.html |title=CHENNAI 28 BOX OFFICE TOP 10 OF 2007 - Behindwoods.com|publisher=Behindwoods.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> Following its theatrical release on 27 April 2007, it received critical acclaim and emerged a surprise [[sleeper hit]], running successfully for more than one year in theaters,<ref name=\"behindwoods.com\"/><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cinesouth.com/specials/specials/tamilcinima2007tam.shtml |title=Tamil cinema in 2007 \u2013 half year report |publisher=Cinesouth.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> whilst going on to achieve [[cult film|cult status]] in the subsequent years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-slide-shows/movie-4/formulaic-films/chennai-28.html |title=Movies that beat the odds - Behindwoods.com|publisher=Behindwoods.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> The film's title is derived from the [[Postal Index Number|pincode]] for [[Mandaveli]], a suburb of [[Chennai]], where the story takes place. The success of the film gained the relatively unknown actors &mdash; Jai, Shiva, Premji and Nithin Sathya, newcomers Vijayalakshmi, Vijay Vasanth and the director Venkat Prabhu popularity.\n\nUpon release, the film was dubbed into [[Telugu language|Telugu]] and released as ''Kodithe Kottalira''.<ref name=\"Telugu Cinema in 2007\">{{cite news | title=hindu.com| work=Friday Review - Cricket theme goes on| url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2007/07/13/stories/2007071350160400.htm | location=Chennai, India| date=13 July 2007}}</ref> The film was also remade in Bengali as ''[[Le Chakka]]'' (2010),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/1100912/jsp/calcutta/story_12922038.jsp|title=Copycat chronicles|date=12 September 2010|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=17 June 2018|location=Calcutta}}</ref> [[cinema of Sri Lanka|Sinhalese]] as ''[[Super Six (film)|Super Six]]'' (2012),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/cricket/ravichandran-ashwin-and-murali-vijay-to-make-special-appearances-in-a-tamil-film|title=Ravichandran Ashwin and Murali Vijay to make special appearances in a Tamil film|date=2016-04-05|access-date=2018-06-17}}</ref> and in Kannada as ''[[Bangalore 560023]]'' (2015).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Chennai-600028-to-be-remade-in-Kannada/articleshow/36190919.cms|title=Chennai 600028 to be remade in Kannada - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-06-17}}</ref> A sequel for the film, ''[[Chennai 600028 II: Second Innings]]'', has also since been released.\n\n==Plot==\nThe story revolves around two local cricket league teams that compete against each other in local matches and consider each other as sworn enemies. Royapuram Rockers are on top of the chain and keep bashing the Sharks year after year. The heroes of the movie are the Sharks' team.\n\nThe story begins when Raghu's ([[Jai (actor)|Jai]]) parents move from Royapuram to Visalakshi Thottam, Chennai 600 028. Raghu is a member of the Royapuram Rockers Cricket team, and a college student living with his parents. He has no choice but to move with them although he detests the area. He is not very excited at the prospect of living in the same area as his sworn enemies. Raghu is faithful to his teammates, but they ignore him because of the distance. Angered at being replaced by a new guy in the team in one of the matches, Raghu estranges himself from cricket and the Rockers.\n\nRaghu informs of Pazhani's ([[Nithin Sathya]]) sister Selvi's ([[Vijayalakshmi (Tamil actress)|Vijayalakshmi]]) love for Karthik ([[Shiva (actor)|Shiva]]) to him. This incident initiates Raghu's friendship with a few Sharks team players and eventually gets induced into the team. Raghu practices with the Sharks to play against the Rockers in the upcoming Radio Mirchi trophy. Pazhani, who soon comes to know of his sister's and Karthik's love affair is disappointed and then there is a tiff amongst the friends. The team splits up for a while, but Karthik apologizes to Pazhani and they make up. The team is united again and they start practicing for the trophy once again. Unfortunately, Karthik gets stabbed by his brother's enemies and is rendered unfit to play the match. Pazhani replaces Karthik as the captain and the team heads for the match.\n\nUnder tight pressure and with a nail biting finish, the Sharks finally defeat the Rockers in the semi-finals of the tournament. In the finals they meet their enemies , a bunch of school kids named Bad Boys-II who practice by bunking school to play cricket on the beach. The kids are really good and the Sharks know it because they have lost to them once before and that too very badly...\n\nThe movie ends with the team really struggling to keep it up in the game.\n\n==Cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Jai (actor)|Jai]] as Raghuvaran \"Raghu\"\n* [[Shiva (actor)|Shiva]] as Karthik\n* [[Premji Amaran|Premji]] as Seenivasan \"Seenu\"\n* [[Aravind Akash]] as Aravind\n* [[Nithin Sathya]] as Pazhani\n* [[Vijay Vasanth]] as Gopi\n* Ezhumalai as Ajay Raj\n* Prasanna as Shanmugham\n* Ranjith as Imran\n* Arun as Uday\n* Karthik as Arivazhagan \"Arivu\"\n* [[Sampath Raj]] as Guna\n* [[Ilavarasu]] as Manohar\n* [[Vijayalakshmi Ahathian|Vijayalakshmi]] as Selvi\n* Kristine Zedek as Swetha\n* [[Badava Gopi]] as Commentator\n* [[Sakthi Saravanan]] as Aravind's boss\n* [[Inigo Prabakaran]] as John (Rockers's captain)\n* [[Mai Prakash]] as Rocker's team player\n* Sundar as Jeeva\n* [[Viraj (actor)|Hari Prashanth]] as Hari, Bad Boys' captain\n* [[S. N. Surendar]] as Sampath, Raghu's father\n* Srilatha as Durga, Raghu's mother\n* [[Shanmugasundaram]] as Sports minister\n* [[Mirchi Senthil]] as Radio Mirchi RJ (special appearance)\n* [[Kalyan (choreographer)|Kalyan]] special appearance in \"Saroja Saman Nikalo\" song\n{{colend}}\n\n==Production==\n''Chennai 600028'' is the directorial debut of Venkat Prabhu.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/features/Interviews/interview-5/director/venkat-prahbu.html|title=Don\u2019t expect another Chennai 28 from Saroja|website=Behindwoods|access-date=2018-06-17}}</ref> He initially titled the film as ''Enga Area Ulla Varaadha'' (''Don't come into our territory''), but lyricist [[Vaali (poet)|Vaali]] was critical of the idea, feeling that the title was \"negative\" sounding. Subsequently, the film was renamed as ''Chennai 600028'', with the idea of including the area's postcode taken from the title of the American television series ''[[Beverly Hills, 90210]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-columns/The-kadalai-man/article14028724.ece|title=The kadalai man|first=Bhargavii|last=Mani|date=30 January 2016|publisher=|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref> Venkat Prabhu felt the new title was \"more apt and universal\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2007/jul/11sld2.htm|title=rediff.com: 'Rajni Sir enjoyed Chennai 600028'|website=www.rediff.com}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Chennai 600028\n| type         = soundtrack\n| artist       = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = <div style=\"white-space: nowrap;\">19 February 2007 {{small|([[India]])}}<br />23 February 2007 {{small|(Singapore and [[Malaysia]])}}\n| recorded     = 2006\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length       = 37:20\n| language     = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| label        = Five Star Audio\n| producer     = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n| prev_title   = [[Deepavali (2007 film)|Deepavali]]\n| prev_year    = 2007\n| next_title   = [[Aadavari Matalaku Ardhalu Verule]]\n| next_year    = 2007\n}}\n\nThe film's score was composed by Venkat Prabhu's brother, [[Premji Amaran]], while his cousin, [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]] composed the soundtrack, which also featured two tracks that were rearranged by Premji. The soundtrack album, featuring 9 tracks, released on 19 February 2007 in [[India]] and four days later in Singapore and [[Malaysia]], on 23 February 2007.<ref name=\"Indiaglitzaudio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/29324.html|title=Chennai-600028 audio on Feb 19|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=indiaglitz.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2009-07-28}}</ref> The audio was launched at the radio station [[Radio Mirchi]], broadcasting all the songs live, which was said to be the first time in India.<ref name=\"Indiaglitzaudio\"/> The lyrics were written by [[Vaali (poet)|'Kavignar' Vaali]] and [[Gangai Amaran]], father of Venkat Prabhu. Also, composer [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]] penned the lyrics for the song \"Natpukullae\", besides singing it. 19 singers had rendered their voice for the songs, including Yogi B, DJ Funky Sathiya and SilveStar, two Singaporean rappers, actor [[Karunas]], director Venkat Prabhu and producer S. P. B. Charan.<ref name=oneindia/>\n\nThe album was both critically acclaimed and gained immense popularity upon its release, being described as, \"excellent\", a \"rocking album\"<ref name=\"Indiaglitzreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/musicreview/8805.html|title=Chennai 600028 - A youthful musical journey|publisher=indiaglitz.com|accessdate=2009-07-28}}</ref> and one of the \"aesthetic highlights\" of the film.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2007/05/04/stories/2007050400100200.htm|title=Leading a winning team - Chennai 600028|publisher=indiaglitz.com|accessdate=2009-07-28|location=Chennai, India|date=4 May 2007}}</ref> The songs were said to be a big hit as reportedly 25000 CDs were sold on the very first day,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/29505.html|title=Chennai-600028 audio a big hit|publisher=indiaglitz.com|accessdate=2009-07-28}}</ref> \"ruling the charts\" worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/30209.html|title=Chennai 600028\u2019s Audio Rules Top 10 List Worldwide!|publisher=indiaglitz.com|accessdate=2009-07-28}}</ref> The songs \"Jalsa\" and \"Saroja Saman Nikalo\" were \"rocking the dance floors\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/30417.html|title=\u2018Jalsa Pannungada\u2019 rocks dance floors!|publisher=indiaglitz.com|accessdate=2009-07-28}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| title8 = Jalsa\n| extra9 = [[Shankar Mahadevan]], [[Premji Amaran]]\n| extra8 = [[Sabesh-Murali|Sabesh]], Gana Ulaganathan, Gana Pazhani, [[Karunas]], [[Premji Amaren]]\n| extra7 = [[S. P. B. Charan]], [[Venkat Prabhu]]\n| extra6 = [[Anushka Manchanda]]\n| extra5 = [[Ranjith (singer)|Ranjith]], [[Tippu (singer)|Tippu]], [[Premji Amaran]], [[Haricharan]], [[Karthik (singer)|Karthik]]\n| extra4 = [[S. P. Balasubramanyam]], [[K. S. Chithra]]\n| extra2 = [[Vijay Yesudas]]\n| extra3 = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n| extra1 = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]], Yogi B, DJ Funky Sathiya, SILVEstar\n| lyrics9 = Gangai Amaran\n| lyrics8 = Gangai Amaran\n| lyrics7 = Vaali\n| lyrics6 = Vaali\n| lyrics5 = [[Gangai Amaran]]\n| lyrics4 = Vaali\n| lyrics3 = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n| lyrics2 = Vaali\n| lyrics1 = [[Vaali (poet)|Vaali]]\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| total_length = 37:20\n| length10 = \n| title10 = \n| length9 = 4:15\n| title9 = Saroja Saman Nikalo\n| length8 = 4:08\n| length7 = 5:01\n| title1 = Ulle Vaa\n| title7 = Yaaro\n| length6 = 4:06\n| title6 = Oh! Oh! Ennanamo\n| length5 = 3:57\n| title5 = Jalsa\n| length4 = 5:15\n| title4 = Yaaro\n| length3 = 2:36\n| title3 = Natpukkullae\n| length2 = 4:09\n| title2 = Un Parvai\n| length1 = 3:51\n| note8 = Remix\n| note4 = Love Theme\n| music9 = Yuvan Shankar Raja\n| music8 = Yuvan Shankar Raja {{small|(Remixed by [[Premgi Amaran]])}}\n| music7 = [[Premgi Amaran]]\n| music2 = Yuvan Shankar Raja\n| note7 = Friendship Theme\n| music6 = Yuvan Shankar Raja\n| music5 = Yuvan Shankar Raja\n| music4 = Yuvan Shankar Raja\n| music3 = Yuvan Shankar Raja\n| music1 = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n}}\n\n== Release and reception ==\nChennai 600028 was released on 27 April 2007, and emerged as a major commercial success. Sify in their review stated that \"All the guys who acted in the film are candid and have let their hair down. RJ Shiva is the surprise packet in the film. Venkat Prabhu deserves a pat on his back for making a breezy fun movie which highlights the fact that cricket in India which is a religion for many is also won through team spirit and sacrifice. So go ahead, make your matinee and enjoy the match.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sify.com/movies/chennai-600028-review--pclwoBaajccbf.html|title=Review : (2007)|website=www.sify.com|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref> Filmibeat reviewed it as \"Apart from cricket there is enough space for love, friendship, sentiments and decent comedy in the script.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.filmibeat.com/tamil/movies/chennai-600028/review.html|title=Read Chennai 600028 Movie Reviews and Critics Reviews|website=FilmiBeat|language=en|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref> Baradwaj Rangan reviewed the film as \"A street-cricket saga from a bunch of no-names comes out of nowhere and knocks your socks off.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://baradwajrangan.wordpress.com/2007/05/31/review-chennai-600028/|title=Review: Chennai 600028|date=2007-05-31|website=Baradwaj Rangan|language=en|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref> Writing for Rediff, the review stated as \"The movie is a result of a perfect team effort in every sense. A perfect entertainer, not to be missed.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/2007/apr/30chennai.htm|title=Chennai 600028: An entertainer|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref>\n\nThe film emerged as a [[sleeper hit]] at the box office, and also emerging as the [[cult status]], in coming years.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"behindwoods.com\" /> The film's 100th day celebrations, took place on 5 August 2007 at [[Chennai Trade Centre]], with [[Rajinikanth]] and [[Kamal Haasan|Kamal Hassan]] being the chief guest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sify.com/movies/chennai-600028-100days-imagegallery-events-jdwmNMfgfcesi.html|title=Chennai 600028-100days|website=Sify|language=en|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref>\n\n== Dubbed versions and remakes ==\n''Chennai 600028'' was dubbed into [[Telugu language|Telugu]] as ''Kodithe Kottalira'' upon release, and the film was remade in [[Bengali language|Bengali]] as ''[[Le Chakka]]'' (2009), and in [[Kannada]] as ''[[Bangalore 560023]]'' (2015). The film was also remade in [[Sinhala language|Sinhalese]] as ''[[Super Six (film)|Super Six]]'' in 2012.\n\n==Sequel==\n{{main|Chennai 600028 II}}\n\nPlans to make a sequel to ''Chennai 600028'' were reported several times in the media, shortly after the first film's release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiaglitz.com/tamil|title=A sequel to Chennai 600028|last=|first=|date=|website=IndiaGlitz.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> It features several cast members from the earlier film including [[Jai (actor)|Jai]], [[Shiva (actor)|Shiva]], [[Premji Amaran|Premji]], [[Aravind Akash]] and [[Nithin Sathya]]. Actors [[Vaibhav Reddy|Vaibhav]], [[Subbu Panchu]], [[Abhinay Vaddi]] were chosen to play supporting roles in the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/kollywood/200416/abhinay-plays-baddie-in-chennai-28-sequel.html|title=Abhinay plays baddie in Chennai-28 sequel!|last=Subhakeerthana|first=S.|date=2016-04-20|website=Deccan Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> Production of the film was officially unveiled on 28 February 2016 and the film was released on 9 December 2016.\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n; [[Vijay Awards]]\n* [[Vijay Award for Best Crew]]\n* [[Vijay Award for Best Find of the Year]] - [[Venkat Prabhu]]\n* Nominated - [[Vijay Award for Best Film]]\n* Nominated - [[Vijay Award for Best Director]] - Venkat Prabhu\n* Nominated - [[Vijay Award for Best Story, Screenplay Writer]] - Venkat Prabhu\n* Nominated - [[Vijay Award for Best Debut Actor]] - [[Shiva (actor)|Shiva]]\n* Nominated - [[Vijay Award for Best Debut Actress]] - [[Vijayalakshmi Ahathian]]\n* Nominated - [[Vijay Award for Best Editor]] - [[B. Lenin]]\n* Nominated - [[Vijay Award for Best Lyricist]] - [[Vaali (poet)|Vaali]]\n* Nominated - [[Vijay Award for Best Male Playback Singer]] - [[S. P. Balasubrahmanyam]]\n* Nominated - [[Vijay Award for Best Choreographer]] - [[Ajay Raj]]\n\n; [[Tamil Nadu State Film Awards]]\n*[[Tamil Nadu State Film Award for Best Family Film]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Enna Kodumai Saravanan Idhu]]\n* [[Kodambakkam, Chennai]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1496380}}\n\n{{Venkat Prabhu}}\n\n[[Category:2007 films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:2000s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:2000s buddy comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s sports comedy films]]\n[[Category:Culture of Chennai]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n[[Category:Films about cricket in India]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Venkat Prabhu]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian buddy films]]\n[[Category:Indian sports comedy films]]\n[[Category:Tamil films remade in other languages]]\n[[Category:2007 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "TMProofreader", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRelease and reception", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chennai_600028"}
{"title_page": "Rosie Jones (comedian)", "text_new": "'''Rosie Jones''' is a British comedian from [[Bridlington]].<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> She has written for panel shows ''[[Harry Hill's Alien Fun Capsule]]'', ''[[Would I Lie to You? (game show)|Would I Lie to You?]]'', ''[[The Last Leg]]'' and ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown]]'',<ref name=\"rts\"/><ref name=\"BBC Rahman-Jones\">{{cite web |last1=Rahman-Jones |first1=Imran |title=Comedian Rosie Jones wants disabled TV characters who are 'gritty and flawed' |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/39588864/comedian-rosie-jones-wants-disabled-tv-characters-who-are-gritty-and-flawed |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=13 April 2017 |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> and has appeared as a guest on ''The Last Leg'', ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats]]'', ''8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown'' and ''[[Hypothetical (game show)|Hypothetical]]''.<ref name=\"C4 8OO10\">{{cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/programmes/8-out-of-10-cats/on-demand/52899-001|title=8 Out of 10 Cats - On Demand - All 4|website=[[All 4]]|publisher=Channel 4|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"C4 Leg\">{{cite web |title=The Last Leg - On Demand - All 4 |url=https://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-last-leg/on-demand/ |website=[[All 4]] |publisher=Channel 4 |accessdate=8 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Countdown\"/><ref name=\"hypothetical\"/> \n\nIn 2018, Jones appeared in ''[[Silent Witness]]''.<ref name=\"EF\">{{cite web |last1=Davies |first1=Katie |title=Interview: Rosie Jones on her Edinburgh debut hour Fifteen Minutes |url=https://www.entertainment-focus.com/theatre-section/theatre-interviews/interview-rosie-jones-on-her-edinburgh-debut-hour-fifteen-minutes/ |website=Entertainment Focus |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> She has performed stand-up comedy at the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]], incorporating her [[cerebral palsy]] into her comedic style; in 2018, she was featured on ''Edinburgh Nights''.\n\n==Career==\nIn 2011, Jones was hired for a year as a junior researcher for [[Objective Media Group]] as part of a disability scheme at [[Channel 4]]. She was unemployed for a few years following this. In January 2015, Jones began a screenwriting class with [[National Film and Television School]].<ref name=\"rts\"/> Jones reached the final of the 2016 [[Funny Women]] Awards.<ref name=\"rts\">{{cite web |last1=Gove |first1=Ed |title=Have you met Miss Jones? |url=https://rts.org.uk/rosiejones |publisher=[[Royal Television Society]] |date=29 November 2016 |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> She began writing for ''The Last Leg'' during their coverage of the [[2016 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"gazette\"/> Jones has also written for ''[[Harry Hill's Alien Fun Capsule]]'', ''[[Would I Lie to You? (game show)|Would I Lie to You?]]'' and ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown]]''.<ref name=\"rts\"/><ref name=\"BBC Rahman-Jones\"/>\n\nIn 2017, Jones appeared on''8 Out of 10 Cats''.<ref name=\"C4 8OO10\"/> In 2018, Jones appeared in ''[[Silent Witness]]''<ref name=\"EF\"/> and on ''The Last Leg''.<ref name=\"C4 Leg\"/> In 2019, Jones was a guest on ''[[Hypothetical (game show)|Hypothetical]]'' and ''8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown'', and again on ''8 Out of 10 Cats'' and ''The Last Leg''.<ref name=\"hypothetical\">{{cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/hypothetical/episodes/1/4/|title=Hypothetical Series 1, Episode 4|publisher=[[British Comedy Guide]]|accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Countdown\">{{cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/programmes/8-out-of-10-cats-does-countdown/episode-guide|title=8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown - On Demand - All 4|website=[[All 4]]|publisher=Channel 4|accessdate=28 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"C4 8OO10\"/><ref name=\"C4 Leg\"/> She has also appeared on the podcast ''[[The Guilty Feminist]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/whats-on/sheffield-date-for-hit-comedy-guilty-feminist-podcast-live-tour-41217|title=Sheffield date for hit comedy Guilty Feminist podcast live tour|last=Armstrong|first=Julia|work=[[Sheffield Star]]|date=15 May 2019|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref> the Channel 4 online programme ''The Last Leg: The Correspondents'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/programmes/last-leg-the-correspondents/episode-guide/|title=Last Leg: The Correspondents - Episode Guide - All 4|website=[[All 4]]|publisher=Channel 4|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref> the [[BBC Three]] series \"Things Not to Say\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcthree/clip/0fc40beb-6cb1-4392-8898-a03b676c9876|title=Things not to say to someone with cerebral palsy|publisher=[[BBC Three]]|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref> [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''Fred at the Stand''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09byv6r|title=Lyons, Mazadza, Jones and Nelson|publisher=[[BBC Radio 4]]|date=31 October 2017|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref> and BBC web series ''Period Dramas''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chortle.co.uk/video/2019/03/08/42483/period_dramas|title=Period Dramas|work=[[Chortle]]|date=8 March 2019|accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Jones launched a new podcast alongside fellow comedian Helen Bauer entitled ''Daddy Look at Me''. The podcast features Bauer, Jones and a guest discussing their childhoods and what they did in order to get attention in their youth.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dessau |first1=Bruce |title=News: New Podcast From Rosie Jones and Helen Bauer With Guests Nish Kumar, Sophie Duker and Ed Gamble. |url=https://www.beyondthejoke.co.uk/content/7329/podcast-rosie-jones |website=Beyond the Joke |accessdate=3 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Jones guest starred in an episode of the third series of the BBC drama ''[[Shakespeare & Hathaway: Private Investigators]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2020-01-21/tamzin-outhwaite-vic-reeves-josie-lawrence-guest-star-in-shakespeare-and-hathaway/|title=Tamzin Outhwaite and Vic Reeves among guest-stars as Shakespeare and Hathaway returns|work=[[Radio Times]]|last=Cremona|first=Patrick|date=21 January 2020|accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref> and on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''The News Quiz'', presented by Nish Kumar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p080pmhs|title=News Quiz host Nish Kumar and the panel take a look at this week's news|date=17 January 2020|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Stand-up comedy===\nJones first performed stand-up comedy without preparation at a friend's comedy night.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/aug/17/rosie-jones-awkward-disability-jokes-edinburgh|title=Rosie Jones: 'People feel awkward about disability so I always have jokes in my back pocket'|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Fleckney|first=Paul|date=17 August 2018|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Jones performed \"Inspiration\" at the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]]. The show was 35 minutes long and contained jokes about her visit to the [[2016 Summer Paralympics]], using disabled toilets, and commentary on the words \"disabled\" and \"[[wikt:spastic|spastic]]\". It received 3.5 stars in [[Chortle]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bennett |first1=Steve |title=Rosie Jones: Inspiration |url=https://www.chortle.co.uk/review/2017/08/08/37389/rosie_jones:_inspiration |publisher=[[Chortle]] |date=8 August 2017 |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> and three stars in ''[[The List (magazine)|The List]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Black |first1=Suzanne |title=Rosie Jones: Inspiration |url=https://edinburghfestival.list.co.uk/article/94524-rosie-jones-inspiration/ |website=[[The List (magazine)|The List]] |date=17 August 2017 |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]'' listed her as one of \"9 hilarious women to look out for in 2017\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clark |first1=Emily-Jane |title=9 hilarious women to look out for in 2017 |url=https://metro.co.uk/2017/01/04/9-hilarious-women-to-look-out-for-in-2017-6248743/ |publisher=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=4 January 2017 |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn 2018, Jones' Edinburgh Festival Fringe show was entitled \"Fifteen Minutes\". Jones talks about a hypothetical \"able-bodied Rosie\" and discusses a sexual fantasy about [[Ryan Gosling]]. She and her routine were featured in ''[[Edinburgh Nights]]'', a [[BBC]] show about the Fringe presented by [[Nish Kumar]]. \"Fifteen Minutes\" received five stars in [[The Arts Desk]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Veronica |title=Edinburgh Fringe 2018 reviews: Rosie Jones/ Marcus Brigstocke/ Alice Snedden |url=https://theartsdesk.com/comedy/edinburgh-fringe-2018-reviews-rosie-jones-marcus-brigstocke-alice-snedden |website=[[The Arts Desk]] |date=17 August 2018 |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> and four stars in [[iNews]],<ref name=\"inews\">{{cite web |last1=Chris |first1=Green |title=Rosie Jones, Fifteen Minutes, review: 'Deliciously dark, original comedy' |url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/rosie-jones-fifteen-minutes-review-a-deliciously-dark-slice-of-originality/ |website=[[iNews]] |date=16 August 2018 |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> [[Chortle]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fleckney |first1=Paul |title=Rosie Jones: Fifteen Minutes |url=https://www.chortle.co.uk/review/2018/08/07/40722/rosie_jones:_fifteen_minutes |website=[[Chortle]] |date=7 August 2018 |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> ''[[The Scotsman]]''<ref name=\"Scotsman\">{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/culture/edinburgh-festivals/comedy-review-rosie-jones-fifteen-minutes-pleasance-courtyard-1-4786905|title=Comedy review: Rosie Jones: Fifteen Minutes, Pleasance Courtyard|work=[[The Scotsman]]|last=Richardson|first=Jay|date=20 August 2018|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref> and Broadway World.<ref>{{cite web |last1=O'Donoghue |first1=Natalie |title=EDINBURGH 2018: BWW REVIEW: ROSIE JONES, Pleasance Courtyard |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/scotland/article/EDINBURGH-2018-BWW-REVIEW-ROSIE-JONES-Pleasance-Courtyard-20180804 |website=Broadway World |date=4 August 2018 |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> It was listed by ''[[Evening Standard]]'' as one of the ten \"best comedy shows to see\" at the festival.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Paskett |first1=Zoe |title=Edinburgh Fringe Festival 2018: The best comedy shows to see |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/arts/edinburgh-fringe-festival-2018-the-best-comedy-shows-to-see-a3891426.html |website=[[Evening Standard]] |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nJones performed at the Greenwich Comedy Festival in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chortle.co.uk/review/2018/09/17/41260/sean_lock,_henning_wehn,_rosie_jones,_tom_lucy_and_kiri_pritchard-mclean|title=Sean Lock, Henning Wehn, Rosie Jones, Tom Lucy and Kiri Pritchard-McLean|work=[[Chortle]]|last=Bennett|first=Steve|date=17 September 2018|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref> In 2019, Jones performed at ''Spectacular'', a one-off event for [[Comic Relief]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bridlingtonfreepress.co.uk/whats-on/theatre-and-comedy/rosie-jones-joins-alan-carr-jimmy-carr-and-sir-lenny-henry-at-comic-relief-spectacular-1-9615693|title=Rosie Jones joins Alan Carr, Jimmy Carr and Sir Lenny Henry at Comic Relief Spectacular|work=[[Bridlington Free Press]]|last=Edwards|first=John|date=25 February 2019|accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comicrelief.com/news/comic-relief-launches-spectacular-night-comedy|title=Comic Relief Launches \"Spectacular\" Night of Comedy|publisher=[[Comic Relief]]|date=3 December 2018|accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref> and appeared at the 2019 [[Women of the World Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/arts/women-of-the-world-at-southbank-centre-lineup-speakers-a4082281.html|title=Women of the World 2019 festival: Line-up, speakers and more for the International Women\u2019s Day event at Southbank Centre|work=[[Evening Standard]]|last=Thomson|first=Lizzie|date=5 March 2019|accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref> She has also been a support act for [[Nish Kumar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yorkpress.co.uk/news/17504331.review-nish-kumar-grand-opera-house-york-march-14/|title=Review: Nish Kumar, Grand Opera House, York, March 14|last=Martel|first=Stuart|work=[[The Press (York)|The Press]]|date=15 March 2019|accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Comedic style==\nJones has [[ataxic cerebral palsy]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stylist.co.uk/opinion/10-things-i-want-you-to-know-about-disability/251253|title=10 things I want you to know about disability|work=[[Stylist (magazine)|Stylist]]|last=Badiozzaman|first=Emily|last2=Jones|first2=Rosie|accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref> she incorporates her slow speech pattern into her comedy, constructing jokes to subvert the punchline that audiences expect.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/><ref name=\"gazette\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gazette-news.co.uk/news/16346906.rosie-joness-slow-talking-quick-thinking-stand-up/|title=Rosie Jones's slow talking, quick thinking stand-up|work=Gazette Standard|last=D'Arcy-Jones|first=Neil|date=11 July 2018|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref> For instance, she has used the opening line \"As you can tell from my voice, I suffer from being northern.\"<ref name=\"rts\"/> Jones unexpectedly refers to previous jokes later in her performances, a trait which one critic describes as \"clinically planned\".<ref name=\"Scotsman\"/> \n\nShe describes her style as \"cheeky\",<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> commenting that she makes jokes that able-bodied people could not.<ref name=\"BBC Rahman-Jones\"/> Jones' stand-up comedy relates to disability and sexuality,<ref name=\"gazette\"/> and has been described as [[dark comedy]].<ref name=\"inews\"/>\n\nIn 2019, Jones received mixed reception for a joke made on ''The Last Leg'' in which she said that as a 16-year-old, environmental activist [[Greta Thunberg]] should be \"drinking Lambrini and getting fingered\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/rosie-jones-greta-thunberg-last-leg-joke-channel-4-new-years-a9266366.html|title=The Last Leg: Comedian Rosie Jones shocks viewers with 'disgusting' and 'totally inappropriate' Greta Thunberg joke|work=[[The Independent]]|last=White|first=Adam|date=2 January 2020|accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|https://rosiejonescomedy.com/}}\n*{{IMDb name|9209882|Rosie Jones}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Rosie}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:British women comedians]]\n[[Category:People with cerebral palsy]]\n[[Category:People from Bridlington]]\n", "text_old": "'''Rosie Jones''' is a British comedian from [[Bridlington]].<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> She has written for panel shows ''[[Harry Hill's Alien Fun Capsule]]'', ''[[Would I Lie to You? (game show)|Would I Lie to You?]]'', ''[[The Last Leg]]'' and ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown]]'',<ref name=\"rts\"/><ref name=\"BBC Rahman-Jones\">{{cite web |last1=Rahman-Jones |first1=Imran |title=Comedian Rosie Jones wants disabled TV characters who are 'gritty and flawed' |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/39588864/comedian-rosie-jones-wants-disabled-tv-characters-who-are-gritty-and-flawed |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=13 April 2017 |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> and has appeared as a guest on ''The Last Leg'', ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats]]'', ''8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown'' and ''[[Hypothetical (game show)|Hypothetical]]''.<ref name=\"C4 8OO10\">{{cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/programmes/8-out-of-10-cats/on-demand/52899-001|title=8 Out of 10 Cats - On Demand - All 4|website=[[All 4]]|publisher=Channel 4|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"C4 Leg\">{{cite web |title=The Last Leg - On Demand - All 4 |url=https://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-last-leg/on-demand/ |website=[[All 4]] |publisher=Channel 4 |accessdate=8 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Countdown\"/><ref name=\"hypothetical\"/> \n\nIn 2018, Jones appeared in ''[[Silent Witness]]''.<ref name=\"EF\">{{cite web |last1=Davies |first1=Katie |title=Interview: Rosie Jones on her Edinburgh debut hour Fifteen Minutes |url=https://www.entertainment-focus.com/theatre-section/theatre-interviews/interview-rosie-jones-on-her-edinburgh-debut-hour-fifteen-minutes/ |website=Entertainment Focus |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> She has performed stand-up comedy at the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]], incorporating her [[cerebral palsy]] into her comedic style; in 2018, she was featured on ''Edinburgh Nights''.\n\n==Career==\nIn 2011, Jones was hired for a year as a junior researcher for [[Objective Media Group]] as part of a disability scheme at [[Channel 4]]. She was unemployed for a few years following this. In January 2015, Jones began a screenwriting class with [[National Film and Television School]].<ref name=\"rts\"/> Jones reached the final of the 2016 [[Funny Women]] Awards.<ref name=\"rts\">{{cite web |last1=Gove |first1=Ed |title=Have you met Miss Jones? |url=https://rts.org.uk/rosiejones |publisher=[[Royal Television Society]] |date=29 November 2016 |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> She began writing for ''The Last Leg'' during their coverage of the [[2016 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"gazette\"/> Jones has also written for ''[[Harry Hill's Alien Fun Capsule]]'', ''[[Would I Lie to You? (game show)|Would I Lie to You?]]'' and ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown]]''.<ref name=\"rts\"/><ref name=\"BBC Rahman-Jones\"/>\n\nIn 2017, Jones appeared on \"8 Out of 10 Cats\".<ref name=\"C4 8OO10\"/> In 2018, Jones appeared in ''[[Silent Witness]]''<ref name=\"EF\"/> and on ''The Last Leg''.<ref name=\"C4 Leg\"/> In 2019, Jones was a guest on \"[[Hypothetical (game show)|Hypothetical]]\" and \"8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown\", and again on \"8 Out of 10 Cats\" and \"The Last Leg\".<ref name=\"hypothetical\">{{cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/hypothetical/episodes/1/4/|title=Hypothetical Series 1, Episode 4|publisher=[[British Comedy Guide]]|accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Countdown\">{{cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/programmes/8-out-of-10-cats-does-countdown/episode-guide|title=8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown - On Demand - All 4|website=[[All 4]]|publisher=Channel 4|accessdate=28 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"C4 8OO10\"/><ref name=\"C4 Leg\"/> She has also appeared on the podcast ''[[The Guilty Feminist]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/whats-on/sheffield-date-for-hit-comedy-guilty-feminist-podcast-live-tour-41217|title=Sheffield date for hit comedy Guilty Feminist podcast live tour|last=Armstrong|first=Julia|work=[[Sheffield Star]]|date=15 May 2019|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref> the Channel 4 online programme ''The Last Leg: The Correspondents'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/programmes/last-leg-the-correspondents/episode-guide/|title=Last Leg: The Correspondents - Episode Guide - All 4|website=[[All 4]]|publisher=Channel 4|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref> the [[BBC Three]] series \"Things Not to Say\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcthree/clip/0fc40beb-6cb1-4392-8898-a03b676c9876|title=Things not to say to someone with cerebral palsy|publisher=[[BBC Three]]|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref> [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''Fred at the Stand''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09byv6r|title=Lyons, Mazadza, Jones and Nelson|publisher=[[BBC Radio 4]]|date=31 October 2017|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref> and BBC web series ''Period Dramas''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chortle.co.uk/video/2019/03/08/42483/period_dramas|title=Period Dramas|work=[[Chortle]]|date=8 March 2019|accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Jones launched a new podcast alongside fellow comedian Helen Bauer entitled ''Daddy Look at Me''. The podcast features Bauer, Jones and a guest discussing their childhoods and what they did in order to get attention in their youth.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dessau |first1=Bruce |title=News: New Podcast From Rosie Jones and Helen Bauer With Guests Nish Kumar, Sophie Duker and Ed Gamble. |url=https://www.beyondthejoke.co.uk/content/7329/podcast-rosie-jones |website=Beyond the Joke |accessdate=3 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Jones guest starred in an episode of the third series of the BBC drama ''[[Shakespeare & Hathaway: Private Investigators]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2020-01-21/tamzin-outhwaite-vic-reeves-josie-lawrence-guest-star-in-shakespeare-and-hathaway/|title=Tamzin Outhwaite and Vic Reeves among guest-stars as Shakespeare and Hathaway returns|work=[[Radio Times]]|last=Cremona|first=Patrick|date=21 January 2020|accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref> and on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''The News Quiz'', presented by Nish Kumar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p080pmhs|title=News Quiz host Nish Kumar and the panel take a look at this week's news|date=17 January 2020|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Stand-up comedy===\nJones first performed stand-up comedy without preparation at a friend's comedy night.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/aug/17/rosie-jones-awkward-disability-jokes-edinburgh|title=Rosie Jones: 'People feel awkward about disability so I always have jokes in my back pocket'|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Fleckney|first=Paul|date=17 August 2018|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Jones performed \"Inspiration\" at the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]]. The show was 35 minutes long and contained jokes about her visit to the [[2016 Summer Paralympics]], using disabled toilets, and commentary on the words \"disabled\" and \"[[wikt:spastic|spastic]]\". It received 3.5 stars in [[Chortle]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bennett |first1=Steve |title=Rosie Jones: Inspiration |url=https://www.chortle.co.uk/review/2017/08/08/37389/rosie_jones:_inspiration |publisher=[[Chortle]] |date=8 August 2017 |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> and three stars in ''[[The List (magazine)|The List]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Black |first1=Suzanne |title=Rosie Jones: Inspiration |url=https://edinburghfestival.list.co.uk/article/94524-rosie-jones-inspiration/ |website=[[The List (magazine)|The List]] |date=17 August 2017 |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]'' listed her as one of \"9 hilarious women to look out for in 2017\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clark |first1=Emily-Jane |title=9 hilarious women to look out for in 2017 |url=https://metro.co.uk/2017/01/04/9-hilarious-women-to-look-out-for-in-2017-6248743/ |publisher=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=4 January 2017 |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn 2018, Jones' Edinburgh Festival Fringe show was entitled \"Fifteen Minutes\". Jones talks about a hypothetical \"able-bodied Rosie\" and discusses a sexual fantasy about [[Ryan Gosling]]. She and her routine were featured in ''[[Edinburgh Nights]]'', a [[BBC]] show about the Fringe presented by [[Nish Kumar]]. \"Fifteen Minutes\" received five stars in [[The Arts Desk]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Veronica |title=Edinburgh Fringe 2018 reviews: Rosie Jones/ Marcus Brigstocke/ Alice Snedden |url=https://theartsdesk.com/comedy/edinburgh-fringe-2018-reviews-rosie-jones-marcus-brigstocke-alice-snedden |website=[[The Arts Desk]] |date=17 August 2018 |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> and four stars in [[iNews]],<ref name=\"inews\">{{cite web |last1=Chris |first1=Green |title=Rosie Jones, Fifteen Minutes, review: 'Deliciously dark, original comedy' |url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/rosie-jones-fifteen-minutes-review-a-deliciously-dark-slice-of-originality/ |website=[[iNews]] |date=16 August 2018 |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> [[Chortle]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fleckney |first1=Paul |title=Rosie Jones: Fifteen Minutes |url=https://www.chortle.co.uk/review/2018/08/07/40722/rosie_jones:_fifteen_minutes |website=[[Chortle]] |date=7 August 2018 |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> ''[[The Scotsman]]''<ref name=\"Scotsman\">{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/culture/edinburgh-festivals/comedy-review-rosie-jones-fifteen-minutes-pleasance-courtyard-1-4786905|title=Comedy review: Rosie Jones: Fifteen Minutes, Pleasance Courtyard|work=[[The Scotsman]]|last=Richardson|first=Jay|date=20 August 2018|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref> and Broadway World.<ref>{{cite web |last1=O'Donoghue |first1=Natalie |title=EDINBURGH 2018: BWW REVIEW: ROSIE JONES, Pleasance Courtyard |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/scotland/article/EDINBURGH-2018-BWW-REVIEW-ROSIE-JONES-Pleasance-Courtyard-20180804 |website=Broadway World |date=4 August 2018 |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> It was listed by ''[[Evening Standard]]'' as one of the ten \"best comedy shows to see\" at the festival.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Paskett |first1=Zoe |title=Edinburgh Fringe Festival 2018: The best comedy shows to see |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/arts/edinburgh-fringe-festival-2018-the-best-comedy-shows-to-see-a3891426.html |website=[[Evening Standard]] |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nJones performed at the Greenwich Comedy Festival in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chortle.co.uk/review/2018/09/17/41260/sean_lock,_henning_wehn,_rosie_jones,_tom_lucy_and_kiri_pritchard-mclean|title=Sean Lock, Henning Wehn, Rosie Jones, Tom Lucy and Kiri Pritchard-McLean|work=[[Chortle]]|last=Bennett|first=Steve|date=17 September 2018|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref> In 2019, Jones performed at ''Spectacular'', a one-off event for [[Comic Relief]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bridlingtonfreepress.co.uk/whats-on/theatre-and-comedy/rosie-jones-joins-alan-carr-jimmy-carr-and-sir-lenny-henry-at-comic-relief-spectacular-1-9615693|title=Rosie Jones joins Alan Carr, Jimmy Carr and Sir Lenny Henry at Comic Relief Spectacular|work=[[Bridlington Free Press]]|last=Edwards|first=John|date=25 February 2019|accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comicrelief.com/news/comic-relief-launches-spectacular-night-comedy|title=Comic Relief Launches \"Spectacular\" Night of Comedy|publisher=[[Comic Relief]]|date=3 December 2018|accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref> and appeared at the 2019 [[Women of the World Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/arts/women-of-the-world-at-southbank-centre-lineup-speakers-a4082281.html|title=Women of the World 2019 festival: Line-up, speakers and more for the International Women\u2019s Day event at Southbank Centre|work=[[Evening Standard]]|last=Thomson|first=Lizzie|date=5 March 2019|accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref> She has also been a support act for [[Nish Kumar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yorkpress.co.uk/news/17504331.review-nish-kumar-grand-opera-house-york-march-14/|title=Review: Nish Kumar, Grand Opera House, York, March 14|last=Martel|first=Stuart|work=[[The Press (York)|The Press]]|date=15 March 2019|accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Comedic style==\nJones has [[ataxic cerebral palsy]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stylist.co.uk/opinion/10-things-i-want-you-to-know-about-disability/251253|title=10 things I want you to know about disability|work=[[Stylist (magazine)|Stylist]]|last=Badiozzaman|first=Emily|last2=Jones|first2=Rosie|accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref> she incorporates her slow speech pattern into her comedy, constructing jokes to subvert the punchline that audiences expect.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/><ref name=\"gazette\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gazette-news.co.uk/news/16346906.rosie-joness-slow-talking-quick-thinking-stand-up/|title=Rosie Jones's slow talking, quick thinking stand-up|work=Gazette Standard|last=D'Arcy-Jones|first=Neil|date=11 July 2018|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref> For instance, she has used the opening line \"As you can tell from my voice, I suffer from being northern.\"<ref name=\"rts\"/> Jones unexpectedly refers to previous jokes later in her performances, a trait which one critic describes as \"clinically planned\".<ref name=\"Scotsman\"/> \n\nShe describes her style as \"cheeky\",<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> commenting that she makes jokes that able-bodied people could not.<ref name=\"BBC Rahman-Jones\"/> Jones' stand-up comedy relates to disability and sexuality,<ref name=\"gazette\"/> and has been described as [[dark comedy]].<ref name=\"inews\"/>\n\nIn 2019, Jones received mixed reception for a joke made on ''The Last Leg'' in which she said that as a 16-year-old, environmental activist [[Greta Thunberg]] should be \"drinking Lambrini and getting fingered\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/rosie-jones-greta-thunberg-last-leg-joke-channel-4-new-years-a9266366.html|title=The Last Leg: Comedian Rosie Jones shocks viewers with 'disgusting' and 'totally inappropriate' Greta Thunberg joke|work=[[The Independent]]|last=White|first=Adam|date=2 January 2020|accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|https://rosiejonescomedy.com/}}\n*{{IMDb name|9209882|Rosie Jones}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Rosie}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:British women comedians]]\n[[Category:People with cerebral palsy]]\n[[Category:People from Bridlington]]\n", "name_user": "Peeyar", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rosie_Jones_(comedian)"}
